        Florence leaves.

        The room feels smaller without her—heavier, as if the weight of betrayal takes up more space than a plant ever could.

        Remedy says eventually, "Well—that was awful." 

        Holloway says, "Yes." 

        I say quietly, "She was right though—about the advice being good, and about you probably not valuing it if it came from her directly." 

        Runner says, "That doesn't excuse the lying." 

        I say, "No—but it explains it." 

        Holloway says (tired), "Explanation isn't justification—Florence had good reasons for what she did. That doesn't make it right." 

        Scout presses harder against my leg; they're confused—they understand betrayal but not the nuance, can't parse the layers of Florence being both wrong and wronged.

        Velvet asks, "What do we do now?" 

        Holloway admits, "I don't know. We have hostile plants threatening our boundary—we have internal trust broken—we have Florence's advice, which might be good but comes from someone we can't trust—and we have…" (gesturing vaguely) "all of this." 

